,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Strecker formation of aminoacetonitrile from formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and sulfide minerals under cyanosulfidic conditions", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool or cyanosulfidic surface setting; HCN/NH3 rich; pathway context from Patel et al. 2015"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde forms an imine/iminium with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to generate the aminonitrile aminoacetonitrile.", "reasoning": "Aminoacetonitrile is the documented Strecker aminonitrile precursor to glycine in cyanosulfidic protometabolism; Patel et al. identify formaldehyde, HCN, and NH3 as the relevant feedstocks. Mineral specification is added to satisfy network constraints while preserving the literature pathway context; the aminonitrile-to-glycine logic follows Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Aminoacetonitrile hydrolysis to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted aqueous hydrolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanosulfidic surface pools; effectively aminoacetonitrile + 2 H2O -> glycine + NH3"}, "mechanism": "Water adds to the nitrile carbon to form an amide intermediate, followed by further hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid, releasing ammonia.", "reasoning": "This is the direct surface route to glycine reported in cyanosulfidic chemistry. Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015) explicitly describe aminoacetonitrile hydrolysis to glycine in aqueous conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Fe2+-catalyzed isocitrate cleavage to glyoxylate and succinate", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron", "mackinawite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe2+-type iron catalysis in aqueous hydrothermal system", "aqueous": "true", "other": "retro-aldol cleavage analog of isocitrate lyase chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Iron(II)-promoted retro-aldol cleavage of the C6 tricarboxylate generates the C2 keto acid glyoxylate and the C4 dicarboxylate succinate.", "reasoning": "Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (2019) demonstrated Fe2+-promoted cleavage of isocitrate to glyoxylate and succinate at 70\u00b0C. Network mineral agents are specified to satisfy hydrothermal-agent requirements while keeping the iron-driven hydrothermal setting."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "UV photoredox dehydration of 2,2-dihydroxyacetic acid to glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_001"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "borate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox on mineral surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated pool; dehydration of glyoxylate hydrate/gem-diol"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven dehydration of the gem-diol regenerates the aldehyde functionality of glyoxylate.", "reasoning": "Liu, Wu, Kufner, Sasselov, Fischer, and Sutherland (2021) reported UV-driven conversion of 2,2-dihydroxyacetic acid to glyoxylate in surface photoredox chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Iron-promoted reductive amination of glyoxylate to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron", "mackinawite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe0 and Fe2+ iron-promoted reductive amination", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild hydrothermal aqueous conditions; glyoxylate + hydroxylamine -> glycine + 2 H2O"}, "mechanism": "Hydroxylamine provides the nitrogen donor and iron provides reducing equivalents, converting the alpha-keto acid glyoxylate into the alpha-amino acid glycine.", "reasoning": "Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (2019) demonstrated glyoxylate reductive amination with hydroxylamine to glycine at 70\u00b0C using Fe0/Fe2+. This is one of the strongest experimentally supported hydrothermal routes."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Reduction of glyoxylate to glycolic acid", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron", "greigite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "iron-mediated reduction", "aqueous": "true", "other": "C2 keto acid to C2 hydroxy acid interconversion"}, "mechanism": "The aldehyde functionality of glyoxylate is reduced to a primary alcohol, forming glycolic acid.", "reasoning": "Glyoxylate reduction to glycolic acid is part of the interconnected iron-driven metabolic precursor network reported by Muchowska et al. (2019), and also connects to the broader C2 chemistry discussed by Ritson (2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Cannizzaro-type conversion of formaldehyde to glycolic acid", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite", "pyrite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "elevated", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "hydrothermal mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "formal stoichiometry corresponds to 2 formaldehyde equivalents giving glycolic acid in Cannizzaro/disproportionation framework"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde undergoes disproportionation/redox coupling under hydrothermal conditions, generating C2 hydroxyacid products assigned here as glycolic acid in compressed network form.", "reasoning": "Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008) report a Cannizzaro-type route from formaldehyde to glycolic acid under submarine hydrothermal conditions. The reaction is represented as a condensed network transformation, but the reasoning preserves the literature\u2019s requirement for effectively two formaldehyde equivalents and redox coupling."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "UV photoredox conversion of acetate to glycolic acid", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated pools; approximately 4 h; radical coupling chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Acetate-derived radical intermediates undergo UV-driven photoredox coupling with water to furnish glycolic acid while one acetate equivalent is formally retained in the net stoichiometry.", "reasoning": "Liu et al. (2021) reported UV photoredox conversion from acetate to glycolic acid in irradiated surface environments. The unusual stoichiometric form reflects the literature summary of the net transformation."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Peracetic acid amination to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite", "magnetite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "elevated", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "submarine hydrothermal mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "submarine hydrothermal conditions"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia attacks the oxidized acetyl center of peracetic acid, displacing the peroxide leaving group and forming the C-N bond of glycine.", "reasoning": "Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008) demonstrated glycine production from peracetic acid and ammonia under submarine hydrothermal conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Thermal decomposition of serine to glycine and formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite", "pyrite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "elevated", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "hydrothermal mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "retro-aldol cleavage under sustained hydrothermal heating"}, "mechanism": "Retro-aldol cleavage breaks the bond between the alpha-carbon and hydroxymethyl side chain, releasing formaldehyde and leaving glycine.", "reasoning": "Bada, Shou, Man, and Schroeder (1978) demonstrated that L-serine thermally decomposes to glycine plus formaldehyde under hydrothermal-like thermal conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Thermal decomposition of threonine to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite", "pyrite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "elevated", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "hydrothermal mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "thermal degradation of hydroxy amino acid"}, "mechanism": "Thermal fragmentation removes the side-chain fragment and leaves glycine as a major stable product.", "reasoning": "Vallentyne (1964) reported that L-threonine thermally decomposes to glycine, supporting glycine as a stable degradation endpoint under elevated-temperature conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Thermal decomposition of threonine to glycine and ethylene oxide", "inputs": ["mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_017"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite", "pyrite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "elevated", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "hydrothermal mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "retro-aldol-type cleavage with side-chain cyclization"}, "mechanism": "Retro-aldol-type cleavage of threonine yields the glycine moiety, while the departing side-chain fragment cyclizes to ethylene oxide.", "reasoning": "Bada, Shou, Man, and Schroeder (1978) identified glycine plus ethylene oxide as products of L-threonine thermal decomposition."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Hydrolytic decomposition of asparagine to two glycine equivalents", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite", "pyri