al_feasibility\": 0.9,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.79,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.76,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.94,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n      \"feedback\": \"Supported by Qian et al. (1993) as a high-temperature hydrolytic decomposition route to glycine. Main issues are network integration and representation: the reaction text says one glycine product node, while the literature indicates two glycine equivalents.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_013\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Represent the stoichiometry explicitly as 2 glycine equivalents\",\n        \"Add upstream origin for asparagine or indicate it as a recycled substrate\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.96\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.77,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.78,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.86,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.8,\n      \"feedback\": \"The downstream Strecker-to-hydrolysis part is strong, but the formaldehyde-to-glycolic acid branch does not actually feed glycine in this pathway as written, and rxn_007 is the weakest reaction in the network. The literature mentions Cannizzaro-type formaldehyde conversion to glycolic acid, but the submitted stoichiometry is oversimplified and the branch is not functionally necessary for glycine production here.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_007\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Correct rxn_007 stoichiometry or replace with a better-defined formaldehyde branch\",\n        \"Make explicit how hydrothermal formaldehyde generation feeds the surface Strecker route rather than conflating it with glycolic acid production\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.97\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.96,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.97,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.98,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.98,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.97,\n      \"feedback\": \"A very strong cross-environment convergence pathway and effectively equivalent in strength to P3. It captures the literature-supported sequence of UV photochemistry generating glyoxylate and iron-driven hydrothermal reductive amination producing glycine.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Retain this as a flagship example of environmental interconnection\",\n        \"Explicitly annotate the surface and hydrothermal agents to satisfy schema requirements\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.87,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This is a good to very good glycine synthesis network with strong literature alignment and genuine convergence on the target. Major strengths are: multiple experimentally supported routes to glycine; well-chosen hubs, especially glyoxylate, formaldehyde, aminoacetonitrile, glycolic acid, and glycine; clear hydrothermal and surface interconnection; and successful production of the target plus downstream biochemical use via glycylglycine formation. The strongest routes are the Muchowska iron network (isocitrate -> glyoxylate -> glycine), the Liu-to-Muchowska cross-environment path, and the Patel aminoacetonitrile hydrolysis route. Main deficiencies are schema-level and network-integration issues: several hydrothermal and surface reactions do not specify the required mineral agents; some stoichiometries are incomplete or compressed (especially aminoacetonitrile hydrolysis, formaldehyde to glycolic acid, and asparagine giving two glycine equivalents); several precursor nodes such as peracetic acid, serine, threonine, and asparagine are introduced